The Technical Deep Dive

I started with exploratory data analysis, moving into data cleaning and preprocessing to ensure a reliable foundation (especially given the noise in historical climate data). I then employed:

    Correlation Analysis (Heatmaps): To identify statistical links between key geographic and climate variables.

    Seaborn Bivariate Analysis (Scatter Matrices): To visualizethe non-linear relationships and density distributions of the data.

    Time Series Analysis (Line Plots): To chart the evolution of average temperatures across centuries.

The Impactful Insights

The results are powerful, confirming and quantifying global climate dynamics:

    Geography of Heat: I established a strong negative correlation (-0.40) between temperature and latitude. Lower latitudes (closer to the Equator) consistently showed higher average temperatures, a relationship clearly visualized by non-linear patterns. Longitude, however, showed no systematic influence.

    A Clear Warming Signal: While historical data (pre-1850) was highly volatile and sparse, the time series plot revealed a stark and significant upward trend starting in the mid-19th century, with a modern shift towards warmer averages.

This was more than just an analysis; it was a powerful exercise in turning raw, noisy data into clear, actionable, and visual stories.

